    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im studying for my materials class and im a bit stuck. why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside concrete for foundations? i get that concrete is strong, but whats the deal with the relationship between its compressive strength and the tensile strength of the steel? like why do they need each other?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Steel rebar and concrete in foundations are a classic example of a symbiotic relationship, much like a very strong, yet slightly clumsy, team-up. While concrete is incredibly robust when being squeezed—that's its compressive strength—it's actually quite weak when being pulled apart, which is its tensile strength. The steel rebar is the hero here, because it possesses that necessary tensile strength, allowing the whole structure to resist those pulling forces that concrete simply cannot handle on its own. Without the steel, the foundation would crack and crumble under the strain, no matter how much concrete you pour.",
      "source": "target",
